LINEAR-COMBINATIONS
<p>
The diagram below can be used to construct linear combinations whose
weights \(a\) and \(b\) may be varied using the sliders at the top.  The
vectors \({\mathbf v}\) and \({\mathbf w}\) are drawn in gray while the
linear combination
$$
a{\mathbf v} + b{\mathbf w}
$$
is in red.
</p>

<p>
  <div style="text-align:center">
  <canvas id="topsliders" width="350" height="100">
    Your browser does not support HTML5 Canvas.
  </canvas>
  <br>
  <canvas id="topcanvas" width="350" height="350" hspace=5>
    Your browser does not support HTML5 Canvas.
  </canvas>
  <script type='text/javascript' src='jslibrary/figures.js'></script>
  <script type='text/javascript' src='jslibrary/linearcomb.js'></script>
  </div>
</p>
=======================================

The diagram available at
\href{http://gvsu.edu/s/0Je}{http://gvsu.edu/s/0Je}
can be used to construct linear combinations whose
weights $a$ and $b$ may be varied using the sliders at the top.  The
vectors ${\mathbf v}$ and ${\mathbf w}$ are drawn in gray while the
linear combination
$$
a{\mathbf v} + b{\mathbf w}
$$
is in red.

